07125nam a22008535i 9781478021599DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021012717  a9781478021599  a(DE-B1597)617415  a(OCoLC)1291507256  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aJV6201b.V53 2021 4aJV6201 7aSOC0150002bisacsh00aViapolitics :bBorders, Migration, and the Power of Locomotion /ced. by Lorenzo Pezzani, Charles Heller, William Walters. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (318 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tViapolitics: An Introduction -- tPart I: Vehicles of Migration -- t1. Capillary Power, Rail Vessels, and the Carceral Viapolitics of Early Twentieth-Century American Deportation -- t2. From Migrants to Revolutionaries: The Komagata Maru’s 1914 “Middle Passage” -- t3. Stowing Away via the Cargo Ship: Tracing Governance, Rival Knowledges, and Violence en Route -- t4. Boxed In: “ Human Cargo” and the Technics of Comfort -- tPart II: Trajectories, Routes, and Infrastructures -- t5. Infrastructures of Escort: Transnational Migration, Viapolitics, and Cultures of Connection in Indonesia -- t6. Routes Thinking -- t7. Historicizing the Balkan Route: Governing Migration through Mobility -- tPart III: The Geophysics of Migration -- t8. The Other Boats: State and Nonstate Vessels at the EU’s Maritime Frontier -- t9. When the “Via” Is Fragmented and Disrupted: Migrants Walking along the Alpine Route -- t10. Deportation and Airports -- tAfterword: For the Migrant, the Way Is the Life -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVehicles, their infrastructures, and the environments they traverse are fundamental to the movement of migrants and states' attempts to govern them. This volume's contributors use the concept of viapolitics to name and foreground this contested entanglement and examine the politics of migration and bordering across a range of sites. They show how these elements constitute a key site of knowledge and struggle in migratory processes and offer a privileged vantage point from which to interrogate practices of mobility and systems of control in their deeper histories and wider geographic connections. This transdisciplinary group of scholars explores a set of empirically rich and diverse cases: from the Spanish and European authorities' attempts to control migrants' entire trajectories to infrastructures of escort of Indonesian labor migrants; from deportation train cars in the 1920s United States to contemporary stowaways at sea; from illegalized migrants walking across treacherous Alpine mountain passes to aerial geographies of deportation. Throughout, Viapolitics interrogates anew the phenomenon called “migration,” questioning how different forms of contentious mobility are experienced, policed, and contested.Contributors. Ethan Blue, Maribel Casas-Cortes, Julie Y. Chu, Sebastian Cobarrubias, Glenda Garelli, Charles Heller, Sabine Hess, Bernd Kasparek, Clara Lecadet, Johan Lindquist, Renisa Mawani, Lorenzo Pezzani, Ranabir Samaddar, Amaha Senu, Martina Tazzioli, William Walters  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBorder securityxSocial aspects. 0aHuman smuggling. 0aImmigrantsxTransportation. 0aRefugeesxLegal status, laws, etc. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh1 aBlue, Ethan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasas-Cortes, Maribel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChu, Julie Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobarrubias, Sebastian, econtributor.4ctb